Typecasting
   Typecasting = changing one data type to another
      example:
            uint8 a = 5;
            uint b = 6;
           uint8 c = a * b; // ❌ error

     Why error?
      a * b → result is uint
      But storing in uint8 → mismatch ❌

Solution (Typecasting)
     uint8 c = a * uint8(b);
      Now:
          b is converted to uint8
           No error ✅

What is uint8?
 Definition:
     uint8 = unsigned integer with 8 bits size

Simple Meaning
      uint → number (only positive)
      8 → size (8 bits)
So:
uint8 = small positive number

Range of uint8
 It can store values from:

0 to 255
 Why?

8 bits → 2⁸ = 256 values
Starts from 0 → ends at 255

 uint8 a = 10;   // ✅ valid
uint8 b = 255;  // ✅ valid
uint8 c = 300;  // ❌ error (too big)

List of Unsigned Integers

👉 Solidity provides:

uint8
uint16
uint24
uint32
...
uint256

👉 It increases in steps of 8 bits


uint8 a = 255;        // small numbers
uint16 b = 1000;      // bigger
uint32 c = 100000;    // even bigger
uint d = 999999;      // very large (uint256)

| Type      | Range           |
| --------- | --------------- |
| `uint8`   | 0 – 255         |
| `uint16`  | 0 – 65,535      |
| `uint32`  | bigger          |
| `uint256` | very very large |

Why so many types?

👉 To save memory (gas)

Small number → use uint8 ✅
Big number → use uint256 ✅












